 This project was designed to enhance digital literacy among first-year B.Tech students at VIT Bhopal. As a Student Digital Ambassador, I explored online tools, built a professional digital portfolio, practiced coding and collaboration platforms, learned proper email etiquette, and studied cybercrime awareness. The project helped me understand safe internet practices, professional online communication, and responsible use of social media. Additionally, it allowed me to reflect on personal habits and develop strategies to improve my digital skills. Overall, the project bridges academic learning with practical digital skills required in the professional world.
       
For Task 1, I created a one-page infographic using [Canva/Prezi/Google Slides]. The infographic covers three main topics: what digital literacy is, useful digital tools for students, and safe internet practices. I included visual elements to make information easy to understand, such as icons for social media safety and graphics for professional online presence.

The most interesting part was designing the visual flow to make the content engaging and easy to read. A challenge I faced was summarizing complex information in a single slide without cluttering it. Overall, this task helped me understand how to communicate digital literacy concepts visually and effectively.

For Task 2, I set up professional profiles on three platforms: GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle. On GitHub, I created a profile README including my name, branch, year, and a short learning goal. LinkedIn contains my education details and aspirations. Kaggle allows me to practice data-related challenges and learn analytics skills.

Each platform serves a different purpose: GitHub for coding projects, LinkedIn for networking and professional visibility, and Kaggle for data science practice. Over the next four years, I plan to maintain these profiles with projects, achievements, and skills to showcase my academic growth and readiness for internships or job opportunities.

For Task 3, I created accounts on HackerRank and Google Forms. On HackerRank, I completed a beginner-level Python challenge “Solve Me First,” earning a completion badge. This helped me practice basic programming logic and understand coding platforms used in interviews.

On Google Forms, I created a 5-question Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz for my batchmates, including multiple-choice and short-answer questions. Responses are linked to a Google Sheet for analysis. These tools will help academically by enabling self-practice in coding and conducting small surveys or quizzes efficiently for collaborative learning.

For Task 4, I drafted two professional emails: one requesting an assignment extension from a professor and another applying for a summer internship. Writing these emails taught me the importance of clear subject lines, proper greetings, structured content, and polite sign-offs.

Additionally, I created a Social Media Do’s and Don’ts checklist to guide responsible online behavior. I realized that careless posts or messages can escalate conflicts or damage reputation. From this task, I learned to always think before posting and communicate professionally online to maintain a positive digital presence.

For Task 5, I studied phishing attacks and created a case study highlighting how students can be targeted via fake emails requesting personal and banking information. The case study describes the steps of the attack, typical targets, and consequences like financial loss and identity theft.

I also developed a “Stay Safe Online” checklist with eight actionable tips, including enabling two-factor authentication and verifying UPI transactions. I was surprised by how easily scams exploit trust and urgency. Personally, I will now verify every financial or personal request before responding and educate peers about safe digital habits.

This project helped me develop essential digital literacy skills for academic and professional life. I learned to build a professional online presence, communicate effectively via email, collaborate using online tools, and protect myself from cyber threats. The hands-on tasks improved my confidence in using digital platforms and understanding safe internet practices. Overall, the project strengthened my technical skills and made me a more responsible digital citizen. These lessons will guide me throughout my B.Tech journey and future professional career.


